metadata.name: Multidimensional Maximalism #118
metadata.description:
Multidimensional Maximalism is my learning experience with layering and composition.

Using the Cellular Automaton algorithm from "Gen., Machina" we create multiple dimensions of life. Each with it's own unique evolution and structure. Like petri dishes in a lab. We then use different compositional elements to explore these dimensions.

100% code - as always.

Available overlays
--
* Lasers (drawing inspiration from The Harvest by Per Kristian Stoveland)
* Circleblend
* Drops
* Lenses
* Squares
* Crazysquares
* Waves
* Tesseract (drawing inspiration from the awesome Tesseract collection by Studio Yorktown)
* None (unlucky you)

Controls (in live view):
--
Press [1-9] to set the export scale ratio
Press [s] to save a high resolution image [ resolution x scale ]

enjoy.

metadata.name: The Artifact #163
metadata.description:
An archaeological artifact from the future, when many everyday objects are produced by generative algorithms. Some artifacts are in one piece, and others are fragmented. The color palettes are named after the rivers where artifacts in this design have first been discovered.

URL and interactive features:

- Append &r=<number> to the URL to change the image resolution. For example, &r=0.5 will halve the pixel count along both width and height, and &r=2 will double it.

- Append &d=<number> to the URL to change the pixel density. For example, &d=0.3 will generate a very quick, coarse render, and &d=2 will generate very fine stippling.

- Append &p to the URL to reveal detailed parameter settings used for the artwork.

- Append &h to the URL to suppress the notification that rendering is in progress.

- Press 's' in the live view to save the rendered image as a png.

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript. Polygon boundaries are determined via t-SNE, which is implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. No external libraries have been used. Licensed CC0.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Glass Worms v2.0 #3
metadata.description:
I'm going back to my first project on fxhash. I take another playful look at shape, form, chaos, and mathematical beauty to create unique and colorful designs made up of translucent glassy elements. In this piece I explore generate another impossible, hovering and spinning glass sculpture. Each unique rendering has a character of its own, some smooth and sensuous while others with sharp color and form changes, ragged edges, and chaotic beauty. Placed over a hilly meadow, with unique lighting to highlight the unusual nature of the glassy worm against a contrasting natural background.

In continuing my exploration of form, organic and digital art is now combined with an animated perspective view. I'm very much enjoying this space, and finding my ground in this new medium.

All proceeds shared with Three.js and Girls Who Code.

Interactive with several user controls:

With the mouse:

Left click and drag to change the viewing angle
Right click and drag to change the view center
Mouse wheel to change the distance to the view center

With the keyboard:

The "f" key will freeze the animation entirely. This can be used if you want to save the image at a certain perspective and location of the glass worm.

Keys "," and "." (or "<" and ">") change the rotation speed left or right. You can stop it entirely, or speed it up to what I consider a reasonable maximum, rotating to the left or to the right. Each time you press, it adjusts the rotation speed

Keys "1", "2", "3", and "4" set the rendering resolution to 1x, 2x, 4x, or 8x the screen resolution. You will see a noticable slow-down in rendering speed.

Key "s" will save to a ".png" file at the rendering resolution (1x..8x screen resolution)
Key "S" will save to a ".jpg" file at the rendering resolution.

metadata.name: Neuromorphosis #148
metadata.description:
The relationship between biology and technology in the future.

Inspired by Neurons and their role in transmitting information, creating dynamic shapes and patterns that evoke brain activity. Where technology and biology combine to create a new form of intelligence and consciousness.

It's a call to reflect on the impact of technology on our society and relationship with humans and the natural world.


🧬 Press "d" to download in png.

🧬 Made with p5.js

metadata.name: A Gift of Nature #114
metadata.description:
Can nature really be a gift if it isn't ours to give?
Do we feel the need to bind it close in the ways of old to live?
If a gift was given would all be forgiven, a place of harmony now we can live in?

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

A gift of nature, sort of. As natural as a digital gift can be. It is a gen art token of my gratitude you might say. It is the younger sibling of "The Spectrum of Nature". 

This is a gift from me to you, a gift of nature that pulls you through. 

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

To know more about the concept and technicalities of this piece, see the fxtext article “The spectrum of nature - a short making of”. However, feel free to skip the article.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Basic info:
The initial render will be 1000px wide and 1000px high. With the ability to scale this up (see below).

The piece uses WebGL, so will perform much better with a graphics card. A faster computer will obviously be better, though I've done my very best to make it fast and efficient for any old laptop. My hope is that you will find the render process quick and enjoyable for the amount of detail that’s present.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Controls:
Press the [s] key to save the initial render. You will need to wait a few seconds after all the elements have stopped loading. For the [s] key to work you may need to open in a new tab. But can right click save otherwise.

Larger sizes:
Press the [2-9] keys to save a resolution of that key size. So [2] saves a 2000x2000 size image, [9] saves a 9000x9000 size image etc. Unless you are making some very large prints you probably won’t need more than 4k (even 2-3k is big). Though the option is there.

There may be slight variations in the textures for the larger renders, this is because the shader code has to redraw the textures at the higher pixel resolution, and getting the textures where they sit is more of an art than a science. All the elements remain exact however.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Made with javascript and some small extra code:
A palette creator by @nathansonic
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.

metadata.name: Geode #29
metadata.description:
A single seed shape is chosen from 13, and placed onto the plane. At every step, a copy of this seed is laid edge-to-edge adjacent to an existing shape, without causing any overlaps. This copy is colored based on the edge it shares with the existing shape. The process continues until the animation completes.

New shapes are placed closest to a moving target. In some mints, this target is slow moving, causing new shapes to expand radially from the seed. In other mints, this target races around, causing new shapes to chase it. 

Each of the 13 shapes forms different patterns under different circumstances. Not all patterns will be explored.

Controls:
  - SPACE: Pause/unpause the animation.
  - ENTER: Skip the animation.
  - R: Restart the animation.

URL Params:
  - "preview=1": Skip the animation.
  - "flex=1": Adapt the boundaries to the size of the window.
  - “slow=1”: Draw only one shape per frame.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: d/e/m/boss TWO #151
metadata.description:
TWO combines a couple of distribution algorithms, one that creates a mesh with different variations and the other that plays with packing probabilities.

Please be patient, it takes a while to render (30-60 secs) and draws around 6M circles during 4 steps.

Responsive, zoom out browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas

TWO is part of a series playing with textures creating emboss/deboss effect.

de/
/boss
em/

100% code, made with p5js
See License.md

metadata.name: glory hole$ #254
metadata.description:
our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

HUGE thank you to @PureSpider for the layered PNG template, this dream would not have been realized without you friend.

metadata.name: Clerestory #230
metadata.description:
Windows welcome daylight, admit fresh air, and offer a view into the outside world. They rarely shatter, always confess the passage of time, and sometimes allow others a chance to look in.

What would the space you're in feel like if it had no windows?

'Clerestory' is an abstract exploration of stained glass windows, drafting shattered sketches for ten potential locations from various perspectives and moments in time. 

Made with WebGL, p5.js, and <3 | CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Oscillators #126
metadata.description:
Click anywhere on the oscillator to play/pause.

3 Rules of Oscillators:
RULE 1, Oscillators should be viewed on Desktop (this is due to the way an oscillator is formed, it requires the display density of the device to be 2 pixels).
RULE 2, Oscillators should be viewed live and not as static images.
RULE 3, Oscillators should be run with the sound on.

Press "S" to Save a version of the Canvas (must be in fullscreen mode)

You are in a dark cave in the Johto region, the year is 1999...

Two synthesizers play a graceful melody atop the shimmering sound of a french horn. A cello provides a deep and haunting counterpoint.

Created with Tone.js and p5js.

Thank you to https://github.com/nbrosowsky/tonejs-instruments for the french horn and cello samples.
